title: Cylindrical rod/tube cutting jig, mounted on 2040 extrusions

description.text: I needed a jig to cut my aluminium rods to size before affixing rod-ends to them for my custom deltabot, so I made these. They were made in a hurry, so it's not perfectly parametric, but should be pretty easy to customize.

• Print both pieces and affix onto 2040 extrusions with M5 screws loosely.
  • Stick the rod all the way in to align the pieces
  • Tighten the M5 screws
  • Use an M3 screw and nut to tighten the clamp on the cutting jig to hold the rod firmly in place while you cut.
  • Saw down the groove in the middle. Try to cut as straight as possible or you'll cut into the plastic, which ruins the jig.

title: Wanhao Duplicator I3 Controller replacement backplate

description.text: The initial batch of Duplicator I3 units could use some extra air intake on the controller. There are air vent holes but no intake holes (at least on my unit). This is a replacement back plate that can be laser cut out of wood or plexiglass or 3d printed. There are two openings that can be left open to allow for air intake or you can install one or two 40mm fans to suck air in to help circulate the air over the power supply and board. The power supply does have a fan that pulls air in but there still needed to be a source for the air.

Laser cut or print. The laser cut parts should have the enclosure holes counter sunk so the original screws can be used. If the part was laser cut in plexiglass then carefully use a larger drill bit with the drill in reverse to make the counter sinks.   
Remove the wiring from the power outlet to the power supply (note where the wires go) and then mount the power socket on the new back plate. Install any 40mm 12VDC fans with the air flowing in towards the controller and connect the fan power to the unused V+ and COM terminals on the DC power supply.   
Reinstall on the back using the original screws.

comments.text: Please note- to install this cover you will need to disconnect the wires going to the power switch. I did this by pulling the connectors off the switch. I see that another user disconnected the wires at the power supply. Either way works. TAKE A PICTURE before you disconnec to help get it back together... This install should take less than 10 minutes.

  • Insert 4 magnets 15mm x 15mm x 5mm inside a slot
  • Insert arm in place and make sure it moves freely
  • Acetone weld or glue base -parts together, move arm peace back and forth until glue or acetone dry out.
  • put 4 magnets other side of kitchen sink and place assembled dishcloth hanger inside of sink at the same place where magnets are in the other side.

title: Adapter for larger spools on Ruperts Horizontal Spool Holder

description.text: The Horizontal Spool Holder by Rupert - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12310 - is brilliantly simple and a quick print when you need something to hold your spools in a hurry without it taking up too much space when not in use. I keep a few of them handy for new printer owners, knowing the frustration of having to improvise something to hold your first roll of filament before you can get started. This thing is an adapter for using larger spools on the horizontal holder. I designed this because I got a spool with a 52mm diameter center hole and some more holes in the side that simply prevents it from resting directly on the horizontal holder. Place this adapter on the horizontal holder and those spools can turn on the adapter instead. To get going: Print one of these if your spool needs it, and one of Rupert's holders to use with it, and ideally three anti-slip rubber feet to put on Rupert's in order to make it stay where it is supposed -- althoug duct tape works if you are in a hurry. :-) November 2016: Added another version that fits the Sculpto filament rolls which have a hole diameter of 57mm, just so you don't have to edit the SCAD for that purpose.
Use a couple of wide bottom layers and ensure that you have a flat first layer to enable the adapter to glide freely on the holder.

The tokens should be held in the visible slots by the bottom edge resting on the top edge if the one below. On this there is too much space between the slots for this to happen. For this to work you need to shorten the vertical distance between the holes so the entire height of the playing field is exactly 6x the diameter of the tokens. description.text: A marble machine based on a third order Hilbert Curve (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_curve) It is sized to be printable on a Printrbot Simple Metal. https://youtu.be/y3rZ8ikVzTk

Print the four pieces and clean them up.
(Prints well without supports.)
(update: wheel gear 5 added and can replace wheel gear 4. It just has more holes for a higher marble flow rate)
Drill out the screw and shaft holes to size, if needed.
Thread 6-32 setscrew hole on the 12-tooth gear
The motor is a 298:1 Micro Gearmotor from Pololu (item #2371)
You will need a couple of screws to attach the motor mount,
a screw to clamp the motor into the motor mount, and a
6-32 set screw to attach the 12-tooth gear to the motor.
You might need to put a screw and washer on the end of the shaft of the large gear to keep it in place, but mine didn't need it.
I used 11/32" ball bearings, 8-9.5mm should work fine.

title: Makerfarm i3v 10" X-Motor One Piece Plate

description.text:
This is a one piece plastic version of the Makerfarm i3v 10" X-Motor plate. It is probably the same plate for the 8" & 12" version. I have test fit this on some spare v-slot 20x20 & fits well. There is a 4 wheel version (rev26) and a 3 wheel version (rev27) The eccentric spacer holes are countersunk, so you do not need a washer where the lock nut attaches. I personally put a washer between the locknut & the plastic. I am waiting on some new wheels before changing this on my printer. My print time for 4 wheel version took 02:34:05 to print & used 1.75oz of PTEG plastic at .6 infill. Update 5/29/2015
Rev27 version. After some further looking at this, I could use even less plastic by cutting the inside corners back. Since only 3 wheels are used, there is really no need for the plastic going all the way to the corners that I can see. After reprinting the 3 wheel version, I like this even better. It feels really solid & a little less weight.
1.56oz at .6 infill of PTEG
Time to print: 02:23:47 I also replaced the support system on rev26 (4 wheel version) as it was a little too close to center side.

Print one of these 3 parts or edit the openscad file (The other stl files are referenced in the openscad file):
i3v_X-MotorMount_NoEarsOrSupportInfill_rev26_repaired.stl
i3v_X-MotorMount_WithEarsAndSupports_rev26_repaired.stl
i3v_X-MotorMount_WithEarsNoSupports_rev26_repaired.stl You will need to cleanup the supports under the motor mount. I used a needle nose pliers for most of this, then some small wire cutters, a file & a dremel type tool. Remove any of the extra plastic from the wheel holes by hand turning a 5/16" bit for the eccentric countersunk holes
& 3/16" bit for the M5 bolts that go on the wheels. Build thread for this design: http://3dprintboard.com/showthread.php?13077-X-Motor-Mount-One-Piece-Print-Idea

This was made in the theory of real firearm suppressors. The baffles fit nicely in the baffle tube and leaves plenty of space for an expansion chamber. If you want a one print build with the same initial idea check out my other suppressor design. This is a must have if you are a sniper/DMR airsoft player, due to the fact that higher fps means more air. You can add steal wool for further sound and vibration absorption.
AND REMEMBER! This is not meant for real steel firearms. AIRSOFT ONLY. Please print responsibly.

Print baffle tube with face down on 20% infill. This reduces amount of filament used, but if you want more strength, you can do whatever you want. Print five baffles cone facing up. print threaded endcap on 20% infill as well. use more precision for threads. All these parts will need to be glued together. I used expanding glue for maximum air seal.
If you do not want print to be shiny or reflective, try sanding the surface and if needed, paint.

description.text:
Addon for Mostly Printed CNC and Mostly Printed CNC, International Edition! For those who don't want to use only zipties for the belts can use this thing. You need to print two left and two right ones.
You need four M4x20 bolts, four M4 nuts, eight M5 bolts with a hook and eight M5 nuts.
The thing (blue) is just put over the existing corner block (white) and fixed by the M4 screw. No need to change anything else on your CNC. Be careful when you tighten the belts! Tighten them a bit and try out the moving of your x and y axis. These belts normally don't stretch, so as soon as your axis work fine you don't need to tighten anymore. I tested it using a corner block from the international edition, but it should also fit on the "normal" version of the CNC/MultiTool. Update 2015-05-30: Version 0.2
Height of the upper bold-mount was increased by 15mm so it now has the same height as the original zip tie hole. I changed it just to be sure there's no downforce when the roller_f is close to the corner block.

I actually made this a while ago right after todbot made his but I got lazy and procrastinated. Anyway here it is... Out of everything I've printed this is definitely the thing I use most often. I made two versions: a desktop one and a wall mounted one. The desktop stand is composed of three parts: a square piece of scrap makerbot wood that I painted black on the bottom, a clip that is glued to the base, and the main housing that holds the cable and snaps in and out of the clip. The wall mounted one is just two parts: the wall mount and the holder of the cable. Again, the holder can snap in and out of the wall mount. I really like the snap fit and it\'s functionally perfect. It makes a very satisfying click and holds it really well. The snap clip allows the cable to be adjusted within the enclosure if needed and also adds some portability. UPDATE:
I've found through repeated use that the snap fit slowly loosens and you have to readjust the position of the iPod charger within the housing. HOWEVER... I just added a new part called the ipodstopper which basically just plugs the bottom whole and keeps everything at the right level and totally eliminates this problem! yay!

Desktop version:
print one of the main bodies: ipoddockv6design (shown in the wall-mounted pic), ipoddockv6botmade (not pictured but basically just labeled BotMade), or ipoddockv3 (plain for you minimalists).
print a bottom clip (ipodflatstandclip) Glue/attach the clip to whatever you want. Pop the cable into the main housing and then pop the main housing on the clip. The fit is intentionally snug so that you don't have to glue it. If you can't get it in just get some sand paper or an x-acto knife and take away a bit of the sides. Shouldn't need much. Wall-Mounted version:
print one of the main bodies (see above for details)
print the wall mount (ipodstandv3) everything should already be in the best orientation to be printed.

description.text:
A stellated truncated dodecahedron.  It is also the logo for Mathematica.  My first two attempts were cut from 3/32" clear acrylic.  The third is 1/8" tinted acrylic.
I calculated the angles for the triangles and connectors using Mathematica.   The angles for the connectors were 65.0126630 degrees,  152.13568896 degrees, and 164.70420180 degrees.  The triangles are isosceles triangles with a base of 1 inch, and a base to side angle of 111.4999145471926 degrees and a side length of 1.36425707926833 for the tall one.  The short triangle had a base to side angle of 123.53604428357949 degrees and a side length of 0.90504049664228.
(Due to an ordering error, the tinted acrylic was .110" instead of 1/8", fortunately I noticed this before I cut the connectors, and so I was able to adjust the slot with in the connectors to compensate for this.)

You need 60 of each triangle, and 60 of each connector.  Use the fat triangles, and the second most obtuse connectors to make 12 pentagons.  Then use the most accucte connector and the tall triangles to make 20 tetrahedrons.  The you can use the most obtuse connector to join these together.  I made two halfs, and then joined them together.  Common mistakes I made were to put the fat triangles in the wrong way.  Make sure the longest side faces the outside of the pentagon.  Also, make sure you don't confuse the two obtuse connectors, as they look very similar.  My first attempt used cyanoacrylate glue, which makes a big mess.  For the second attempt I used plastruct bondene, which worked a lot better.
The sheets of parts have been offset .004" to account for the kerf of the laser cutter.
The tinted spikey was assembled using weld-on acrylic cement.  This is by far the best way I have found to glue acrylic.  Just put a drop on the joint, and capillary action will draw the glue into the joint.  It sets enough to let go in about 30 to 45 seconds.

The goal of this project was to develop a low cost, open source inkjet printer utilizing standard inkjet technology, for personal use. This project was partly in response to the fact that there are no DIY inkjet kits available. There was a kit available from Parallax www.parallax.com/dl/docs/prod/robo/InkjetKitDocs-v1.0.pdf. This kit is no longer made and the book http://www.amazon.com/Inkjet-Applications-Matt-Gilliland/dp/0972015930 that was written to use that kit is now out of print.
The prototype design used a carriage assembly constructed from steel rods that were assembled using connectors that can be printed on an FDM machine. The entire carriage system is driven along the x-axis by a belt attached to a stepper motor. The print cartridge, taken from an HP point of sale printer, is driven along the y-axis by another stepper motor belt drive. The electronic controls use an Arduino Mega to run all of the printing systems.
The design resulted in a working prototype that fulfills all of the design constraints. The rod frame carriage design is lightweight, easy to assemble and easy to integrate with the other systems. The Arduino used in the electronics has a large library of resources available to perform things like LCD, SD card, and stepper control.
Areas where future work should be focused include making molds and casting printable parts to bring down the overall cost, developing host side software, and optimizing the speed. There is a video of this working here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fYeYeTGkvJM
There are additional pictures here: http://www.flickr.com/photos/nicholasclewis/sets/72157626730985822/ This was a group project involving:
Patrick Hannan
Jared Knutzen
Nicholas C Lewis
Joy Markham

Print the parts contained in the "Mechanical.zip" file and assemble them as shown in the "DIY Inkjet Printer.pdf".
Assemble the electrical components as shown in the "Circuit.zip" & "DIY Inkjet Printer.pdf".
Flash your Arduino Mega with the firmware from "Firmware.zip".
Use Processing.org to run the script in "Preprocessor.zip" and create a 'print.dat' file. Copy the file onto the SD card and print using the DIY Inkjet Printer. Optionally don't build the x-y carriages and just mount the print head to other robots for mobile printing applications.
